olcock Jones (1804-1863), whose family owned more than one hundred slaves. While extensive, these letters can provide only one part of the story of the Jones family plantations in coastal Georgia. In this remarkable new book, the religious historian Erskine Clarke completes the story, offering a narrative history of four generations of the plantations' inhabitants, white and black.Encompassing the years 1805 to 1869, Dwelling Place: A Plantation Epic describes the simultaneous but vastly different experiences of slave and slave owner. This "upstairsdownstairs" history reveals in detail how the benevolent impulses of Jones and his family became ideological supports for deep oppression, and how the slave Lizzy Jones and members of her family struggled against that oppression. Through letters, plantation and church records, court documents, slave narratives, archaeological findings, and the memory of the African-American community, Clarke brings to light the long-suppressed history of the slaves of the Jones plantations-a history inseparably bound to that of their white owners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aAfrican AmericanszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aPlantation lifexHistoryx19th centuryxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aPlantation lifezGeorgiazLiberty CountyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPlantation ownersxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aPlantation ownerszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aSlavesxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aSlaveszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aWhitesxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aWhiteszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of